efore the startup of the changed system.  Operations personnel that work with the SCR system receive initial training on the applicable operating procedures as well as refresher training on the procedures or whenever there is a change to the procedures.

The operating procedures contain a description of the step by step instructions required to start up the entire SCR system, whether this is the initial startup, a startup following a normal or emergency shutdown, or a major change that requires a Hazard Review.  The procedures also describe the operating limits of the SCR system.  Procedures are also in place for the shutdown of the SCR system under both normal and emergency conditions.  Normal operations for the entire SCR system are also described.  Temporary and emergency operations are conducted in the same manner as normal operations.  Other procedures have been developed for the unloading of aqueous ammonia from a tanker truck to the storage tanks and for sump pump operation.  The aqueous ammonia unloading procedure was developed in collaboration with the ammonia suppliers and PG&E.

Safety and health considerations for the safe handling of aqueous ammonia are discussed in Section 1.6.1 and in the MSDS sheets.  The following systems have been implemented in the aqueous ammonia storage facility to ensure safe operations of the aqueous ammonia system. 

1. Shutoff valves on the aqueous ammonia feed line, which will close automatically if:
    - The low flue gas flow rate alarm is triggered
    - The high ammonia/air volume ratio alarm is triggered, or
    - The flue gas SCR reactor inlet low temperature alarm is triggered;
2. Ammonia flow meters on the ammonia feed lines;
3. Liquid level indication and high level alarm for each storage tank, easily visible from the unloading
   position;
4. Indication of storage tank level, system pressures, pressure relief valve position and alarm status in
   the plant control room;
5. Shutoff valves located on

the storage tank fill lines, which will close automatically if the high-
